            break;
        }
    }
}
```

    In this example, the coroutine is not yet ready when `poll_next` is called, so it returns `Pending`. When it becomes ready (in this case, after a single iteration of the loop), `poll_next` will return its value.

    Using `Poll::Pending` instead of `Poll::Ready` implies that your asynchronous code can be paused at certain points and resumed later. This is useful when you need to perform some I/O operation or wait for an event.

