The provided `is_subdirectory` function uses `canonicalize()` to normalize the paths before checking if the parent path of the first path starts with the second path. This can be inefficient for very large directory structures because it involves creating intermediate files and reading their metadata.

    To improve efficiency, we can use a different approach that only compares the base names and extensions of the paths, regardless of their full canonicalized forms.
    ```code
fn is_subdirectory(path: &Path, base_path: &Path) -> bool {
    let path_base = path.file_name().unwrap();
    let base_base = base_path.file_name().unwrap();
    let path_ext = path.extension().map_or("", |s| s.to_str().unwrap());
    let base_ext = base_path.extension().map_or("", |s| s.to_str().unwrap());

    path_base == *base_base && path_ext == *base_ext
}
```
    This version of the function is significantly faster because it only compares the base names and extensions, rather than the full canonicalized paths.

    Another approach to improve efficiency would be to use `path::PathBuf` instead of `std::path::Path`, which allows for more efficient path manipulation operations.
